 of virgin, asexual wife/mother, and whore. Instead we find images of the sexual woman, who enjoys her body without any sense of shame; the mother, who nurtures her children without sacrificing herself; and the warrior woman, who actively resists demands that she conform to one-dimensional stereotypes of womanhood.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAfrican diaspora. 0aBrazilian literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aCuban literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aWomen and literaturexAmerica. 0aWomen and literaturezAmerica. 0aWomen in literature. 0aYoruba (African people) in literature. 0aYoruba (African people)xBrazil. 0aYoruba (African people)xCuba. 0aYoruba (African people)zBrazil. 0aYoruba (African people)zCuba. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women in Religion. 4aLatin American, Caribbean, and Latinx Studies : Latin American Studies. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / Hispanic American.2bisacsh1 aChaviano, DaÍna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConceição, Sônia Fátima da, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCunha, Helena Parente, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEsteves, Sandra MarÍa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvaristo, Conceição, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcÍa, Cristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLorde, Audre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorejón, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPérez, Loida Maritza, econtributor.4ctb4https